@ibuenros For this reason, I have added logging of the JVM input arguments when the app_master and container start. That way it is easy to figure out what the port will be.

That said, maybe the â€œtokenâ€ should be `$PORT_<REQUESTED_PORT>` like `$PORT_10001`.  If port 10001 is open we take it.  If not we try 10002.  And so on.  It will still be â€œrandomâ€ in Yarn because there are multiple container on the same node, so the JVM input argument logging will still be needed.  

As a longer term item, it would be really nice to be able to â€œclassifyâ€ the ports and expose them via the admin UI.  That way I could see a list of nodes, see what containers exist, see the â€œopenâ€ ports, etc.

It would be better if you can make this modification `Source` agnostic so we don't have to add similar features to each `Source`.

Basically, a config called `state.store.ignore.previous.state`. If set to try to returns in an empty `Collection` of `WorkUnitState`s when `getPreviousWorkUnitStates` is invoked.

It should be a simple change to the `JobState` class. Specifically, on the following line: https://github.com/linkedin/gobblin/blob/master/gobblin-runtime/src/main/java/gobblin/runtime/JobContext.java#L139

The line would be changed to something like:

```
if (jobPropsState.contains(ConfigurationKeys.SOURCE_STATE_IGNORE_PREVIOUS_STATE, false)) {
  this.jobState = new JobState(jobPropsState, new HashMap<>(), this.jobName, this.jobId);
} else {
  this.jobState = new JobState(jobPropsState, this.datasetStateStore.getLatestDatasetStatesByUrns(this.jobName), this.jobName, this.jobId);
```

@chavdar thoughts?
